
This paper reviews age differences in emotion processing and how they may relate to age-related changes in the zzso Compared with younger adults, older adults react less to negative situations, ignore irrelevant negative stimuli better, and remember relatively more positive than negative zzso Older adults' ability to insulate their thoughts and emotional reactions from negative situations is likely due to a number of factors, such as being less influenced by zzso cues, selecting different emotion regulation strategies, having less age-related decline in prefrontal regions associated with emotional control than in other prefrontal regions, and engaging in emotion regulation strategies as a default mode in their everyday zzso Healthy older adults' avoidance of processing negative stimuli may contribute to their well-maintained emotional zzso However, when cardiovascular disease leads to additional prefrontal white matter damage, older adults have fewer cognitive control mechanisms available to regulate their emotions, making them more vulnerable to zzso In general, although age-related changes in the brain help shape emotional experience, shifts in preferred strategies and goal priorities are also important zzso 

